footer: footer.title: {[Helvetica x 16]}{[8.0 x 11, 5.656 x 5]}{[normal x 16]}{[null x 15, NORMAL]} //^{a Estimated via ordinary least squares regression models adjusting for blocking and stratifciation variables (Hampden County geography, household} size and composition, gender of household head, and implementation wave); AMPM interview characteristics (frist or second interview, weekend indicator, and respondent characterization of intake relative to usual levels); respondent demographics (baseline age group, gender, and race/ ethnicity); usual reported intake measures from the EATS instrument; and baseline composite scale measures of availability of fruits and vegetables in the home; positive attitudes about foods, fruits, and vegetables; and perceived barriers to grocery shopping and to consumption of fruits and vegetables. All analyses incorporated sampling weights accounting for the unequal probability of respondent selection across strata and for survey nonresponse. To account for respondents with more than one follow-up interview, SEs and test statistics are heteroscedasticity-robust and clustered _{b at the respondent level.} Outcome data from sampled respondent survey, pooled early and late post-implementation sample. Units for outcomes defned as described in the_{48} _{c Food Pattern Equivalents Database.} _{d Regression-adjusted mean intake.} Price elasticity calculated by dividing estimated impact expressed in proportional terms by the proportional change in the price of targeted fruits and _{e vegetables earning the HIP rebate (0.3).} Boldface indicates difference in regression-adjusted means between HIP group and non-HIP group was statistically signifcant; two-sided test: *p< 0.05; **p< 0.01; ***p< 0.001. HIP, Healthy Incentives Pilot; AMPM, Automated Multiple Pass Method; EATS, Eating at Americas Table Screener.
